title: Machete - big ass knive - Halloween prop

description.text:
I needed a machete for a Halloween party I'm attending, to match my costume. Unfortunately I wasn't able to find any here, so I stepped in and created one myself.
This is a rater large model, consisting of two parts:
Blade (~490mm)
Handle (~180mm)
Both together are about 610mm long.
Most likely you will have to cut it down to match your print bed's size. I used a normal netfabb license to cut it into five seperat pieces.
This thing isn't sharp, al the edges are rounded. I wasn't able to print it fully so far, got my printer still going with another model. As soon as I'm able to finish this project I will post pics.

Combining everything together I added two long tubes into the blade, so you can use an aluminium/steel/wooden rod to support the model, and to get everything cut down by netfabb back together. Use aceton to glue the pieces to each other.
The rod has to be about 800mm long in total. Each tube is 438mm long, but a 400mm rod, glued in place, will be sufficient.
The blade and handle are secured by two M4 screws (12mm long) and two nuts. I printed the handle just now and finished it with cold aceton vapour. Printed with a .6mm nozzle at .17mm layerhight. Little mishappening with the soldering iron, when I inserted one of the nuts. Overall it doesn't bother me.

I wanted to have a piece of Mac OSX (which -in my opinion- is the best-looking operating system) on my desk. I have chosen the paper bin of Mac OSX because it is at first a really good-looking piece of design and represents the philosophy that even a container for waste can look great. Secondly, it was a good chance to enhance my modelling-skills, which are not that good. I used Google SketchUp for modelling and I think that I nearly reached the point where SketchUp was not able anymore to create what I wanted. Anyhow, feel free to print out your own paper bin with that nice design and please post your pictures of them :) I used the following settings for printing:
Layer height: 0.12mm
Wall thickness: 0.2mm
retraction: enabled, only if jumps are bigger than 3mm
retraction-speed: 60mm/s
speed: 40mm/s
nozzle-size: 0.4mm

description.text:
I designed this Elder Wand from pictures after watching the Harry Potter movie series again in anticipation of Halloween.  It is divided into two pieces so that it will print on the Replicator 5th generation printer bed (though I am sure it will work on others as well).  To assemble, simply match the two inserts and fill with a little glue to make the join permanent.
As you can see from the pictures, the dimpling in the handle seems to have been picked up well with printing at standard resolution.
Happy printing, and please let me know if you have made one.

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Standard

Infill:

20%

Notes: For good detail, I printed at a travel speed of 90mm/s instead of the default 150. I recommend printing completely horizontal with supports so that the print layers appear like wood grains. I used 2 shells and 10% infill, and it is a little flimsy at the tip, so I would recommend 3 shells and 20% at least. Change this to match your desired weight and feel.

description.text:
Has some blockhead come along and broken your mother's doorbell by excessively pounding on it? That's what happened to my mom, not just once either...
So instead of spending money on buying another doorbell button that will just break again, I decided to make something stronger, better... not sure about the faster part, but you get the idea. Unfortunately no one had/has made one on Thingiverse, so I was forced to make one myself and now I'm sharing it, so in case any poor soul out there needs one... It's there. I suggest printing it with natural ABS to get the best results, my doorbell has a light behind the button and it still shines through the new one.
In fact, I can't even tell if there was a difference from before, it looks exactly the same. Mission accomplished and my mother is happy.

• Get your sad broken doorbell button down and give it shelter from the people who abuse it.

  • Turn over your doorbell button and remove all parts from inside (i.e.: light bulb contact board & the metal contact springs). If your metal springs are pressed in, use a small standard screw driver to pry them out. Do it gently so you don't ream out the channels that they were pressed into.

  • Remove the sad broken button and replace it with the brand new button that you just made.

  • Reinsert all the guts and rejoice, you're done fixing the button. Your mother/father/spouse/siblings/overlord/master will be pleased.

description.text:
This is a playable Bb Herald Trumpet. You can listen to me playing it here: https://youtu.be/qL3ms7lRvDc I printed it on a MakerBot as 10 pieces which were assembled and then bonded together using acetone. It plays about 20 cents flat, likely because my Bach 3C mouthpiece doesn't insert as far as my design intended. The tone quality isn't bad. I rendered it using ReplicatorG. I set the slice layer to 0.2mm, the shells to 3, and the infill to 20%. The STL files were generated using a C# program I wrote. The mathematical model for the bell is loosely based on a paper which appeared in a January 2011 issue of Journal of the Acoustical Society of America by Charles Macaluso and Jean-Pierre Dalmont called "Trumpet with near-perfect harmonicity: Design and acoustic results". The pieces print with fins that stabilize them against wobbling or tiping during printing. The fins are designed to snap-off after printing. It has been pointed out that the fins may not be necessary; a one-line change to the C# program can remove them; if you try it, let me know how that works. PLEASE improve this! Next steps:
  • Make it print in fewer pieces by placing more than one piece on the print platform
  • Curve the trumpet so it is easier to hold (and not a herald trumpet)
  • Add rotary or piston valves so it can play chromatically in the lower register
    • Thanks to my employer, Microsoft, for lending the MakerBot on which this was printed.

Provides a girdle for the y-axis servo motor.  Goes underneath the perspex.  
Tension is increased by turning a pair of bolts on the back side of your Thing-o-Matic.

• Forgive the code; I've printed and am using the product so I'm lacking enthusiasm for code cleanup :-)

  • Print the object

  • Locate: 2 M3x16 bolts, 2 M3 washers, 2 M3 nuts
    • 3.5 Loosen the y-axis stepper

  • Open up the bottom of the 'bot. Disembowel it.

  • Unplug the y-axis stepper

  • Place the nuts in the t-slots. Sticky-tape them into place.

  • Place girdle over the stepper, nuts down. The bolts will wedge the girdle against the perspex. The girdle fits around both the stepper and the bolts/endstop for the nearby z-axis rod.

  • Take a breath, and drill some holes through the back of your makerbot. I just eyeballed this. You might find a clever way to judge where to put the holes - you know, measuring and stuff like that....

  • Washers on bolts, bolts through hole into nuts. Tighten.
    • 8.5. recable stepper

  • re-tighten y-axis-stepper bolts. Actually, I don't seem to have done that....

  • Reembowel your makerbot

  • Bottom on, and hope your makerbot still works...
    • Notes:
  • I "stripped" one of the nut-holes; I added glue and all is well.
    • Possible improvements:
  • nut-holes could possibly have their tolerances tightened
  • thin plane of plastic to be wedged between stepper and perspex; may make fitting easier.

Sliding element is basically aluminum square tube with UHMWPE pads. The square tube pieces are made using SVG templates. UHMWPE pads are cut out from channel stock, drilled and fitted inside, held by plastic screws. Some hacksaw (or Dremel) work is required to thin the areas where UHMWPE pads touch the angle rail. description.text: Thanks to Bryan for the source code! Please go see the original source files for this, Bryan made it very easy. It's made for a microswitch with 2mm mounting holes spaced 6mm apart. Edit the code to change that if you need (in the section labeled // Holder screwholes ) Example switches: http://www.amazon.com/Momentary-Hinge-Lever-Micro-Switch/dp/B008SO0IGQ/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&qid=1444758567&sr=8-3&keywords=microswitch On the very last line, change the ## for length. Example here is 61mm ( switch_arm(61);) . I moved the holes closer to the edge so that there is enough overhang for the microswitch past the arm. Printed with 30% infill. Doesn't really matter. Just don't get a switch that has "snap" in the description, you want a microswitch with barely any resistance so that it triggers when dropped instead of letting the entire carriage unload

These connect two parts together by sliding the keyed piece into the slot on the other piece until the overlapping edges snap over the ends, providing a secure connection. The variables given to the modules let you easily resize the connectors in length, width, and depth, as well as change the dimensions of the key, making it stronger in certain directions if needed, or preventing incompatible versions of a design from being connected.
If you make one or use these files, please give me feedback! I'm currently without electronics for my Prusa so I can't test and revise the fit yet. Probably nothing that can't be fixed during cleanup with a file or a heatgun.
EDIT: I have made a "flush fit" version with the locking tabs recessed into the part. With this version, the x, y, z dimensions specified are the maximum outer dimensions. The tradeoff is that the bit reinforcing the key from twisting is thinner. EDIT EDIT: The flush fit .stl and .scad now have the male connector rotated so it prints without impossible overhangs.

The x, y, and z parameters are the outer dimensions of the whole connector. The key_x, key_y, and key_z parameters are the dimensions of the key, with the exception that key_y has a y_overlap added to the key to give it a secure base where it meets the mounting block, and a matching cutout on the female connector. The y_overlap formula could be increased to create a stronger attachment to the key if the connectors need to hold under more force. I just chose values that didn't create overly thin looking pieces.
